Organic LPG has arrived in the Czech Republic, promises ecological operation
Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) is a well-known alternative fuel in the Czech Republic.
It is especially popular for its significantly lower price compared to gasoline or diesel, given a significantly lower excise tax, but its benefit is also in lower CO2 emissions per kilometer driven.
Like petrol and diesel, it also has its environmentally friendly variant - "bio LPG".
But this is quite new - it first appeared on the European market last year and arrived in the Czech Republic a few days ago, according to a press release from the Czech LPG Association.
"These days we have received the first fifteen tons of bio-LPG, which will be distributed to our gas stations in combination with the classic fossil LPG," said Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD> Karl<0xC3><0xAD>k from Primagas.
However, bio LPG cannot be taken as bioethanol or biodiesel.
According to the association, it is chemically identical to the classic oil LPG, which many motorists are now refueling in their cars.
Therefore, it is also possible to mix both versions arbitrarily.
"The only difference from the classic LPG is the method of production," says Ivan Indrá<0xC4><0x8D>ek, chairman of the association, about bio LPG.
This is also one of the great advantages of bio LPG compared to other alternative fuels.
It is easy to transport and store, and the distribution infrastructure is quite good, e.g. compared to hydrogen or electricity.
Currently, this gas is obtained as a by-product in the production of bioethanol from food residues and sugar cane.
In the future, it should also be produced in a targeted manner, e.g. from cellulose biomass, i.e. from wood waste.
In contrast, conventional petroleum LPG is produced partly as a by-product of oil refining, partly by separation in natural gas extraction.
As a result, depending on the production technology and source, the operation of a bio-LPG car is 40-70% more environmentally friendly in terms of the carbon footprint than the operation of an oil LPG and up to 90% compared to diesel.
However, it is not about CO2 emissions from the exhaust of the car, but about the ecology of fuel production, the so-called "well-to-tank" part (in Czech "from source to tank").
One of the largest producers of bio LPG is currently the petrochemical companies Eni, Total and Neste.
According to a recent update of the National Clean Mobility Action Plan (NAP <0xC4><0x8C>M), Unipetrol is also exploring the possibility of production at its Lithuanian refinery.
According to the association’s estimates, there are about 170,000 LPG vehicles in the Czech Republic; the Ministry of the Environment reports a slightly higher number, about 200,000, in the NAP <0xC4><0x8C>M.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Transport, almost 6 thousand conversions of cars to LPG were carried out last year alone.
It is possible to refuel LPG in the Czech Republic at about 950 stations of various operators.
