North America has been inhabited for 30,000 years, scientists say
Findings from the Chiquihuite Cave in Zacatecas, Mexico, include 1,930 limestone tools, including fine blades that could be used to cut meat, and pointed objects that could serve as spearheads or spears.
Scientists have found that the oldest of the tools come from 33,000 to 31,000 years ago.
"There are only a few products of this age.
But there they are," said archaeologist Ciprian Ardelean of the University of Zacatecas and lead author of one of two studies published in the journal Nature.
The youngest tools reach the age of 12,500 years.
According to experts, the people of the Chiquihuite cave, located at a great altitude, inhabited for a long 20,000 years.
Until now, the generally accepted theory has been that the first representatives of the species Homo sapiens crossed the land bridge from the area of present-day Russia to Alaska about 13,500 years ago.
Archaeological evidence, including unique spearheads used to kill mammoths and other prehistoric animals, has shown that this Clovis culture subsequently spread across much of North America.
However, this model has been fractured in recent decades when several ancient settlements were discovered that were two to three thousand years older.
The second study, published in the journal Nature, reports 42 different sites across North America that prove human presence on the continent as early as 26,000 to 19,000 years ago.
Scientists believe that a small number of people may have arrived on the North American mainland earlier than previously thought.
Some of them came to America by ship.
"It's clear that people were in America long before the development of the so-called Clovis culture," said anthropologist Ruth Gruhn of the University of Alberta in Canada.
