The air in your home is five times worse than the air outside.
Health Harms Air Fresheners and Deodorants
Health is threatened not only by poor air quality in outdoor areas, but also at home.
This was pointed out by Israeli human health expert Carol Abraham, quoted by The Jerusalem Post.
According to Abraham, who helped create Israel’s environment ministry, household pollutants need to be addressed now that many people are spending more time working from home.
According to the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), the quality of indoor air is up to five times worse than outdoor air.
The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that 3.8 million people die prematurely each year due to poor air quality in their homes.
“Due to the coronavirus epidemic, which has forced many and still forces people to work from home, people need to spend more hours at home than before, so it’s time to focus on air quality in homes,” she said.
In Israel, almost no one is concerned with the quality of "home air".
Dangerous things can be things that a person usually comes into contact with - paints, air fresheners, disinfectants, deodorants or pesticides.
"The poisonous gas is also emitted by the clothes we regularly wear to the dry cleaners," Abraham said.
Children, elderly members of the household and people with respiratory problems are the most at risk.
Even otherwise healthy individuals may begin to suffer from problems such as headache, fainting, irritation of the nasal passages, nosebleeds, vomiting or skin allergies.
With prolonged exposure to unhealthy substances, internal organs and the central nervous system can be damaged.
Not all pollutants come from objects inside homes, and the source may also be the material from which houses are built.
